2. oum . . . Poenis: the chronological order is neglected for the sake of the rhetorical arrangement, two kings and two nations. Philip V of Macedon and Antiochus the Great, king of Syria, were both brought into conflict with Rome by their attacks upon Perga- mus and the RhodianS, allies of the Roman people. Philip was defeated at Cynoscephalae in 197 13.c., and Antiochus at Magnesia in 190 B.c. The Aetolian league had joined Antiochus against Rome. The three Punic wars originated in the Carthaginians attacking Messana in Sicily, Saguntum in Spain, and King Masinissa of Nu- midia respectively. In the case of Saguntum, the Romans took no adequate measures to succor their allieS, though they made the destruction of the city a cause of war. Compare the reply given by the Spanish chief when Rome attempted to gain his aid against Hannibal (Liv. 21. 19. 9), Quae verecundia est, Romani, postulare vos uti vestram Karthaginiensium amicitiae praeponamus, cum qui id fecerunt (i.e. Saguntinos) crudelius quam Poenus hostis perdidit, vos socii prodideritts.
